Mandatory vaccinations for NHS staff in England might soon be dropped because Omicron is less severe than previous Covid variants, according to a minister. The government made it mandatory for frontline NHS workers to be fully vaccinated by 1 April back in the Autumn, meaning workers would have to get their first jab by this Thursday, 3 February. If they chose not to get vaccinated they would be redeployed or dismissed from the NHS. Approximately 77,000 workers (5% of the NHS workforce) in the health service are currently unvaccinated. There are already close to 100,000 vacancies in the NHS and it is under immense pressure from the Covid backlog. Chief secretary to the treasury Simon Clarke explained on Monday that the mandate could now be reversed. Speaking to Sky News, he said: â€œWe have been trying to strike, throughout this pandemic, the right balance between having the maximum impact in terms of measures that support public safety in the face of the virus, but also have the minimum impact in terms of our freedoms as a society.â€ He said the Delta variant was â€œextremely dangerousâ€ and took a â€œhuge toll on our societyâ€, meaning it was important to protect anyone going into hospital. Clarke said that while Omicron is highly transmissible and dominant in the UK, the fundamental facts have changed because this variant is not as dangerous as Delta. â€œAny decision taken today will reflect those policy changes,â€ Clarke explained. However, he did clarify that this decision lies with the health secretary, adding: â€œThe point is we need to wait until he and such colleagues have had a time to look at that.â€ He said this doesnâ€™t change that the most vulnerable people in society still need to be vaccinated. Simon Clarke MP discusses reports the govt may step back from requiring mandatory COVID jabs for NHS workers, saying Omicron is a "less severe" variant and any decision will "reflect that reality".#KayBurley: https://t.co/zWKHeXNS3YğŸ“º Sky 501, Virgin 602 an